surveys.narrative: Natural reproduction of Bluegill and Northern Pike has been documented. There was no evidence of natural reproduction by Largemouth Bass. Adult game fish present in the fishery are from past stockings. Black Bullhead and White Suckers are present but in low numbers.

Florian reservoir is a small body of water (50 acres) that is primarily managed for bluegill, largemouth bass, and northern pike. Most angling is based from the fishing pier that is located in the park, or from shore by the dam. There is a boat access on the reservoir. Gas-powered outboard motor use is not allowed, but boaters may use oars or electric motors.

Catchable-sized sunfish are stocked annually in early June. The bluegill population consists mainly of fish that are seven inches or longer. Northern pike are commonly caught by anglers, and fish up to 30 inches long were sampled in 2006. Largemouth bass abundance is presently low.

Florian Reservoir, in Marshall County, is a 50-acre reservoir located approximately 1.5 miles southwest of the city of Florian in northwestern Minnesota. Florian Reservoir is part of the Tamarac River watershed, and was constructed in 1975 by damming the Tamarac River near Florian. Florian Reservoir is located within Marshall County Park and is the only fishing lake in Marshall County.

Most angling is based from a handicapped-accessible fishing pier located in the County Park, or from shore by the dam. There is a boat ramp on the river within the County Park. Gas-powered outboard motor use is not allowed, but boaters may use oars or electric motors.

Florian Reservoir is prone to fish kills during winter. Several styles of aeration systems have been used to prevent winterkill, but none have been successful.

A fisheries survey conducted in 2017 documented the presence of Black Bullhead, Bluegill, Northern Pike, Pumpkinseed, Rock Bass, and White Sucker. Bluegill and Northern Pike are the two fish species most commonly targeted by anglers fishing at Florian Reservoir.

Northern Pike are more tolerant of low dissolved oxygen concentrations than most other game fishes, so they continue to be available for anglers each year. Most Northern Pike are less than 25 inches long, but there have been fish up to 15 pounds sampled in the reservoir.

Catchable-sized Sunfish are stocked in June each year. Most of the stocked fish are longer than 6 inches.

Bluegill, and Northern Pike, introduced spring of 1987, both produced a year class. Largemouth bass failed to do so, however, Walleye introduced to provide primarily males and were not expected to produce year class. Walleye fingerlings, planted fall, 1987, are to help provide bio-control of Black Bullhead which have reappeared. The Walleye will help provide a base upon which to rebuild the recreational fishery. Florian reservoir is expected to provide excellent bass/panfish fishing and fair Northern Pike fishing.

Florian Reservoir, in Marshall County, is a 50-acre reservoir located approximately 1.5 miles southwest of the city of Florian in northwestern Minnesota. Florian Reservoir is part of the Tamarac River watershed, and was constructed in 1975 by damming the Tamarac River near Florian. Florian Reservoir is located within Marshall County Park and is the only fishing lake in Marshall County. A fisheries survey conducted in 2014 documented the presence of Black Bullhead, Northern Pike, Pumpkinseed, Rock Bass, and White Sucker.

Northern Pike trap net catch rates in 2014 was 1.3 fish/net and just below the 20-year average of 1.45 fish/net. The average Northern Pike length was 18 inches, with fish ranging from 14 to 34 inches. Ageing analyses revealed most pike were age-0 to age-3 indicating either the population is self-sustaining or is replenished from upstream migrants.

Panfish catch rates in 2014 were low. Pumpkinseed catch rates were 1.3 fish/net and fall below the 20-year average of ~2 fish/net. Average length of Pumpkinseed was 3.5 inches and fish ranging from 3 to 4 inches. Five Rock Bass were sampled that ranged from 5.5 inches to 7.5 inches in length with an average length of 6.2 inches. To supplement low panfish numbers, stocking will be done in the spring of 2015.

Black Bullhead catch rates were 9.3 fish/net and is well below the 20-year average of 65 fish/net. Black Bullhead length ranged from 4.7 inches to 9.5 inches, with an average length of 6.3 inches in length.

Florian Reservoir located mostly in a county park was created in 1975, and is a small shallow reservoir that is aerated to avoid winter kills. A diffuser aeration system was installed in 1999, which is a big improvement over the previous pump and baffle system that was used. It is managed primarily for bluegill and largemouth bass, with fishable populations of northern pike and black crappie. Adult bluegill are stocked every year at a rate of 80 pounds per acre (400 pounds total). They were not stocked in 2000 due to budget cuts, so the population was lower in 2001. The bluegill stocking program will continue. High populations of bullheads that prey on young-of-year bluegill and other species are making it hard for other them to reproduce successfully. Most fishing pressure is from the MN DNR fishing pier, or from shore by the dam. There is also a public access located in the park.

A fisheries survey conducted in 2022 documented the presence of Black Bullhead, Black Crappie, Bluegill, Northern Pike, Pumpkinseed, Rock Bass, White Sucker, and various small non-game species. Northern Pike and panfish provide the primary angling opportunity in Florian Reservoir. In 2022, two Northern Pike were sampled with the larger being 25.5 inches. Florian Reservoir is a small impoundment (50 acres) that is managed for bluegill, largemouth bass, and northern pike. The reservoir is accessible through Florian County Park, which is administered by Marshall County. An aeration system is operated on the lake in the winter. This system creates open water, so extreme caution is advised.

Most angling is based from a fishing pier within park, or from shore. There is a boat access on the north side of the reservoir, located within the county park. Gas-powered outboard motor use is not allowed, but boaters may use oars or electric motors.

Catchable-sized sunfish are stocked annually in early June. The bluegill population consists mostly of fish that are seven inches or longer. Northern pike are commonly caught by anglers. Largemouth bass abundance is presently low.
